Old tiles, cracked or broken tiles and missing grout let down the look of the bathroom. Fix everything that needs fixing first and you will be amazed at the improvement. It doesn't take long to learn how to tile and fix grout either––a little trial and error practicing and you'll soon feel comfortable doing it yourself. The main thing with tiling is to have patience and to observe accuracy without compromise––it's not a job you can rush. Sometimes changing the color of the tiles can completely change the feel of the bathroom. The effort to do this can be well worth it, and tiles are generally quite affordable for the budget renovator. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c0/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/c/c0/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-1Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-1Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

If you need to fix the grout, see grouting a tile floor, regrouting tile, whitening grout and cleaning grout. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/29/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/29/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-1Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-1Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

A new coat of paint transforms a room. If your bathroom walls are covered in wallpaper, remove the old paper with a steamer (you can rent one for the weekend.) If you're painting over paint, remove all flaked, sticky, dirty areas by cleaning and lightly sanding over them. Ensure that the walls are free of mildew and damp before painting––if you do have recurring mildew, check the source and add mildew inhibitor to your paint. Place painter's masking tape over all edges you don't want painted (moldings, tiles, wood, etc.) and cover furnishings, the tub and shower, etc. with drop cloths to catch paint splashes. Paint stains cheapen the finished look, so avoid them in the first place. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/2f\/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-459px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/2\/2f\/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet1.jpg\/v4-759px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Neutral colors are best for longevity of bathroom style, particularly when selling the house. Stick to creams, beiges, whites and other low-key colors and use accessories to add splashes of color to the bathroom. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a5\/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet2.jpg\/v4-459px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/a5\/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet2.jpg\/v4-759px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Consider contrasting paint colors to highlight areas, such as window sills and bathroom cabinets, where relevant and appropriate. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/aa\/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet3.jpg\/v4-459px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","bigUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/a\/aa\/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet3.jpg\/v4-759px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-2Bullet3.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Wait for the sales on paint if you're really wanting to save a lot. If you know a painter, you might be able to get trade prices if he or she is willing to help buy it for you.

You can upgrade your shower and tub fixtures in an afternoon. Most of these kits come with a very detailed set of instructions. Changing the taps/faucets, shower head and soap holders can really lift a bathroom. Be sure to match the colors though––having some brass and some silver looks mismatched and is something that you can easily remedy. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/25/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-459px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/2/25/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-6Bullet1.jpg/v4-759px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-6Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
</p><p><br />
</p></div>"}

What do you do if you want to replace, say the shower cubicle, but not the bath, but the colors are a mismatch? Try painting or re-tiling with colors that do match, to draw away the eye from the mismatch. In the case of bathtubs, these can be repainted using specialist paints and a lot of grunt. Even plastic or acrylic bathtubs can be recolored if need be. {"smallUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e0/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-459px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"https://www.wikihow.com/images/thumb/e/e0/Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-6Bullet2.jpg/v4-759px-Remodel-Your-Bathroom-on-a-Budget-Step-6Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":334,"bigWidth":760,"bigHeight":552.2527472527472,"licensing":"<div class="mw-parser-output"><p>License: <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/3.0/">Creative Commons</a><br>
